-- Field Journal pen: Eero Mattila (Trails & Open Country desk). Summer 2026 batch.
insert into public.blog_posts (
  slug, title, kicker, excerpt, category_slug, tags, hero_image, hero_alt,
  content, author_id, author_snapshot, status, published_at, featured,
  read_time_minutes
) values (
  'twelve-kilometres-at-one-in-the-morning',
  'Twelve kilometres at one in the morning',
  'Kiilopää · July · Trails',
  'A night hike on the marked trails above Kiilopää, in which the sun refuses to leave, the reindeer hold a meeting on the path, and the mosquitoes stay in the valley where they belong.',
  'stories',
  ARRAY['hiking','kiilopaa','urho-kekkonen-national-park','midnight-sun','summer']::text[],
  '/images/summer-fell-boardwalk-1200.webp',
  'Wooden boardwalk trail crossing open fell tundra under a bright golden night sky',
  '[{"type":"paragraph","text":"The car park at Kiilopää was almost empty when I laced my boots at half past eleven in the evening, and the woman locking the fell centre door looked at my pack and nodded the way you nod at someone doing a sensible thing. That nod is the whole point of this entry. In July, above the Arctic Circle, starting a hike at midnight is not an adventure. It is the correct reading of the conditions, and the locals have known it for as long as there have been locals."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"The logic is simple and nobody tells you until you get here. In the middle of a warm July day the fells are hazy, the light is flat and white, and the mosquitoes in the birch zone are running a full economy. At night — the word still means something, even when the sun stays up — the air cools, the light drops into that long low gold that lasts for hours, the haze settles, and the insects mostly clock off. Same trail, same legs, a different planet."},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Up through the birch, out onto the open fell"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"The marked trail climbs from the fell centre through the last of the mountain birch and then breaks out onto open ground, and the transition is as sharp as a doorway. Below the line: green shade, soft ground, the smell of leaves, a persistent whine near the left ear. Above the line: wind, lichen, a floor of broken stone that clicks underfoot, and a horizon that suddenly includes most of the visible world. The mosquito that had been escorting me since the car park turned back at the treeline like a border guard at the edge of his jurisdiction."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"The boardwalks up here are their own small pleasure. Weathered grey duckboards, two planks wide, laid decades ago across the wet sections and rebuilt plank by plank ever since. At one in the morning, with the sun low to the north, every board carried a stripe of gold down its length, and the walking made that hollow wooden drum sound that I associate with every Finnish national park I have ever been in. Somewhere below, a stream ran loud with the last of the snowmelt. I stopped and filled my bottle where the water came fast over stones, the way I always have up here on the high fells, and it was cold enough to hurt my teeth. I am telling you what I did, not what the safety leaflet tells you to do. The leaflet says treat your water. Make your own decision on the high ground and stand by it."},{"type":"pullquote","text":"Below the treeline the mosquitoes run the economy. Above it, the wind holds office hours all night."},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"The meeting on the path"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"Forty minutes above the treeline I came around a shoulder of the fell and interrupted a meeting. Eleven reindeer stood on and around the trail — I counted them twice, because there is not much else to count at one in the morning — including two calves of the year with legs like folding rulers. Reindeer in July are shedding, ragged, and supremely unimpressed. The nearest one looked at me for perhaps four seconds, decided I was neither wolf nor employer, and went back to the lichen. I stood still for a while and then walked slowly through the middle of the meeting, and they parted around me at a polite radius of ten metres, the calves keeping their mothers between us."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"They belong to somebody, of course — every reindeer in Finland does, there is no such thing as a wild one here — and their being spread across a national park fell at night is just the summer arrangement. The herds drift up onto the high ground in July for the same reasons I was there: the wind, the cool, and the absence of insects. The reindeer worked all this out several thousand years before the fell centre installed its first sauna."},{"type":"image","src":"/images/summer-fell-boardwalk-1200.webp","alt":"Wooden boardwalk trail crossing open fell tundra under a bright golden night sky","caption":"Duckboards above the treeline, around one in the morning. The sun sits low to the north and stays there.","full":true},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"What the night hike asks of you"},{"type":"list","items":["Check the route length and your own honesty before starting. Twelve kilometres on open fell at night is a joy in good weather and a serious errand in bad. The forecast changes fast up here and there is no treeline to hide behind.","Carry a head net and repellent even for a night hike. The high ground is mostly clear, but the first and last kilometres are in the birch zone, and the birch zone in July does not forgive optimism.","Warm layer and a wind shell, always. It was nine degrees on the summit shoulder in July with a steady northerly. Down at the car park it had been twenty-two.","Tell someone where you are going, even in the nightless night. The light makes everything feel safe. The distances have not read the marketing.","Take more photographs on the way out than feels reasonable. The light between midnight and two is the best you will ever hike in, and it does not come back at noon.","Leave the earbuds in the car. The fell at night has a very quiet soundtrack — wind, water, stone underfoot, the click of reindeer somewhere off the trail — and it is the actual product."]},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Coming down"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"I got back to the car park a little after three. The sun had begun its slow climb back out of the northern low point, the light shifting from gold towards ordinary morning, and two other cars had arrived — trail runners, judging by the shoes, making the same calculation I had made four hours earlier from the other direction. We nodded at each other. It is a good nod. It means: you also read the conditions correctly."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"I drove down towards Saariselkä with the windows open and the heater on my feet, which is a July combination in Lapland that I refuse to apologise for. Behind me the fells were turning white-gold at the edges. Somewhere up there the meeting was presumably still in session, eleven delegates and two apprentices, chewing lichen in the wind, waiting for the humans to go back to sleep so the fell could get on with its actual business."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"Written from Saariselkä the following afternoon, with a faint boardwalk rhythm still in both calves and one mosquito bite behind the left ear, acquired in the last four hundred metres of birch."}]'::jsonb,
  NULL,
  '{"handle":"eero","display_name":"Eero Mattila","avatar_url":null}'::jsonb,
  'published',
  '2026-07-01'::timestamptz,
  false,
  9
)
